00:48:06.510 --> 00:48:09.840
about conservation, which we
haven't talked too much about.

00:48:09.840 --> 00:48:13.650
For example, my understanding is
that Germany has invested a lot

00:48:13.650 --> 00:48:18.160
in passive solar housing,
much better insulated housing.

00:48:18.160 --> 00:48:20.350
That kind of thing's probably
been pretty important.

00:48:20.350 --> 00:48:23.680
I know as a homeowner I
don't do as much as I would

00:48:23.680 --> 00:48:27.930
if I had more economic incentive
to do it, like a carbon tax.

00:48:27.930 --> 00:48:29.560
But I'm certainly
aware of a bunch

00:48:29.560 --> 00:48:31.630
of stuff I could
do in my own house.

00:48:31.630 --> 00:48:34.370
It just-- my intuitive
sort of understanding

00:48:34.370 --> 00:48:39.770
is that we have a huge way to
go in just conservation alone,

00:48:39.770 --> 00:48:42.820
and that could potentially
be a huge source of savings.

00:48:42.820 --> 00:48:45.500
But could you comment on that?

00:48:45.500 --> 00:48:47.560
KARA MILLER: Conservation
is the unsexy portion

00:48:47.560 --> 00:48:48.785
of talking about the climate.

00:48:48.785 --> 00:48:50.160
KERRY EMANUEL:
But it's something

00:48:50.160 --> 00:48:51.493
that we're in control of, right?

00:48:51.493 --> 00:48:53.700
If you own a house or
you are contemplating

00:48:53.700 --> 00:48:56.360
buying a car or
anything else, you

00:48:56.360 --> 00:48:57.800
can control that to some extent.

00:48:57.800 --> 00:49:01.500
And I think you're absolutely
right that the average person

00:49:01.500 --> 00:49:03.270
is going to respond,
at some level,

00:49:03.270 --> 00:49:06.160
to incentives and disincentives
to do this sort of thing.

00:49:06.160 --> 00:49:09.760
And buildings are about a
third of the power consumption,

00:49:09.760 --> 00:49:11.860
vehicles another third.

00:49:11.860 --> 00:49:15.710
Industry is, I think--
very, very rough numbers.

00:49:15.710 --> 00:49:20.560
So if you can beat these down,
it can make a big difference.

00:49:20.560 --> 00:49:24.390
And we costed out at MIT,
what would it actually cost

00:49:24.390 --> 00:49:27.676
us to comply with the gold
standard green regulation

00:49:27.676 --> 00:49:28.800
in building a new building?

00:49:28.800 --> 00:49:31.690
And the funny thing is,
we surveyed our students

00:49:31.690 --> 00:49:35.040
and faculty about what they
thought the cost excess would

00:49:35.040 --> 00:49:38.060
be, and it ranged
from 20 to 70%.

00:49:38.060 --> 00:49:40.770
The actual numbers are
very close to zero.

00:49:40.770 --> 00:49:42.480
And that sort of
surprised me, too.

00:49:42.480 --> 00:49:44.340
And it turns out that
they're close to zero

00:49:44.340 --> 00:49:47.930
because if you have more
insulation, more energy

00:49:47.930 --> 00:49:49.740
efficiency, you're
generating solar,

00:49:49.740 --> 00:49:53.010
you don't need to buy as
big a ventilation system,

00:49:53.010 --> 00:49:54.090
for example.

00:49:54.090 --> 00:49:55.770
There are cost savings.

00:49:55.770 --> 00:49:58.880
And when you sum it all up,
it's pretty close to zero.

00:49:58.880 --> 00:50:01.710
And I think when
more people find out

00:50:01.710 --> 00:50:04.420
that they can do all
this at very little cost

00:50:04.420 --> 00:50:06.260
to themselves-- and
of course, over time,

00:50:06.260 --> 00:50:08.100
a big economic
benefit-- it's going

00:50:08.100 --> 00:50:10.644
to happen in a more
widespread way.

